 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utrevize.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trevize</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.angelfire.com/journal/MnM/images/tacobell.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(2/27/01 2:02:25 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Faydedar gettin nerfed o rsomething.</span><hr size=1> I dunno guys.<br>
<br>
I'd like to see Verant put &quot;epic&quot; into the druid epic.  <br>
<br>
If you really think about it.  The druid epic is VERY easy on the diffaculty scale but EXTREMELY boring due to the camping factor.<br>
<br>
I agree with most the posts that I really don't want to suddenly see every druid with their epic as standard equiptment.  That wasn't the intent.  I also agree that the quest as it is today it just a tedius long boring camp from beginning to end.  Changing Faydedar only solves a very small peice of the over all problem.  <br>
<br>
I don't know the solution.  I just hope Verant can come with with a good solution that doesn't ruin the quest and make it stupidly easy and therefore the druid epic becomes common and all the other classes have yet another thing to add to the bitch about druids list.  The other concern is if the quest goes under a major change what of all the druids that have quest componets already...  <br>
<br>
I don't see an easy way out...<br>
<br>
Maybe if Faydedar did become a triggered spawn, he should certainly get a good buffing.  ie.  level 60+ dragon, more hitpoints etc.  His loot drop table is already very nice.  Waterdragon Shield is on par with Serv and Talendor shields.  But Serv and Talendor are level 60 dragons.  /boggle<br>
<br>
Camping is what make the druid epic hard.  That really needs to be changed to less camping but harder things to kill imo.<br>
<br>
 <p>-Trevize - 60th Heirophant -Drinal
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utwygg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Twygg</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(2/27/01 2:22:17 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Faydedar gettin nerfed o rsomething.</span><hr size=1> Here's something to think about:<br>
How many people are impressed when they see a high-level rogue with a Ragebringer? (no one)<br>
How many people are impressed when they see a high-level cleric with a Sprinkler? (not many)<br>
How many people are impressed when they see a high-level druid with a Nature Walker's Scim? (almost everyone)<br>
<br>
<br>
Personally, I thought the whole Faydedar thing was very in-character, and very fitting to the quest.<br>
<br>
The corrupted portion of the quest starts with low-level mobs, and builds up to the epic, Faydedar.  Most who have actually camped and killed Faydedar will agree that the hours that follow his initial spawn are by far the most exciting moments of their entire EQ carreers.  And the final moment when he dies, and you loot the Pod are the ultimate climax to the epic quest.<br>
<br>
His elusiveness, and the small margin for error are what make him so difficult.  If he were as simple and predictable as a triggered spawn, it wouldn't be nearly as exciting.  There would really be no climax to the epic quest.<br>
<br>
The Faydedar kite is the ultimate test of a druid's kiting ability.<br>
<br>
Kiting Raptors is an excellent way to pass the time while waiting for him to spawn if you don't want to use  a mule.  After each kite, take a 30 second run south of the raptor island and med out on the water while tracking for him.  If it winds up being a 1-week camp, at least you'll gain a level or two.  There's also so many people out there with 2 accounts and 2 computers, you could probably find a friend who would be willing to put a mule on the spires for you.<br>
<br>
There really are options to this.  You could camp him an hour or two every couple days.  Eventually he'll show up.  There's no need to make it a marathon camp.  I work an average of 61 hours a week (No, not all of us are losers).  I camped him a couple hours a day until he finally showed.  It was a good time to catch up on paperwork, house cleaning, etc.<br>
<br>
Don't beg for a shortcut for this quest.  Complete it the way it is.  When you finish it, the elation you feel will make it all seem worth it.  If Faydedar is handed to you on a platter, the quest and the Nature Walker's Scimitar become something less than impressive.  The weapon itself is not awesome.  But it's a symbol that tells everyone, and especially yourself, that you were able to complete the greatest quest you may ever come upon.  Don't focus on the stats or the effects of the weapon itself.  Think about what it symbolizes. <p><center><a href="mailto:twygg@prexus.com">Twygg</a> of <a href="http://www.prexus.com/">Prexus</a><br>
